25|$|Japanese-Canadian {{women and}} {{children}} faced {{a specific set of}} challenges that greatly affected their way of life and broke down the social and cultural norms that had developed. Whole families were taken from their homes and separated from each other. Husbands and <b>wives</b> <b>were</b> almost always separated when sent to camps and, less commonly, some mothers were separated from their children as well. Japanese-Canadian families typically had a patriarchal structure, meaning the husband was the centre of the family. Since husbands were often separated from their families, <b>wives</b> <b>were</b> left to reconfigure the structure of the family and the long established divisions of labour that were so common in the Japanese-Canadian household.|$|E
